CP TEXT:
Thus we advocate that United States Supreme Court should affirm the Third Circuit Court decision in New Jersey Department of Environmental Protection v. United States Nuclear Regulatory Commission. This endorsement should be taken as an act of comic democratic enunciation.
This competes:

A) It&amp;#39;s a fundamentally different plan—your entire 1AC is dedicated to framing arguments about how we need to take up the position of the analyst—our argument is not that you should take the position of the tragic psychoanalyst but instead you should take the role of democratic life coach, endorsing the plan—cx of the 1AC demonstrates that their framework arguments are the intrinsic focus of the debate—how the affirmative is framed and endorsed matters

B) We fundamentally do not agree that despair is foundational—there is no mythic or totally successful political act, but the result of this reasoning should not be to describe despair, but instead to advocate a politics of comic possibility—we are essentially PIC-ing out of the way you foreground the importance of your affirmative—understanding the aff as part of a continuing political project of democratic possibility rather than an epic break with previous political failures

C) At worst you can just reject the do the plan part of our advocacy but still embrace a comic frame to adjudicate the debate—their solvency evidence is terrible, and specific to terrorism but not specific to the relationship between terrorism and trauma—we’d still win the debate

D) We advocate roleplaying an ascent into politics instead of a descent into catastrophe—this PICs out of the framing of the aff—because the plan can’t solve the root cause identified by the 1AC, better to positions ourselves to politics with an attitude that there is more to be done rather than regarding a single Supreme Court decision as messianic
And our comic frame solves all your affect and trauma arguments

